text: Love the tutorials Corey they help so much in learning Python. Just thought I would update this video because the syntax is off around 8:00. The quick fix is to add "with open('new_names', 'w', newline='') as new_file:" and the issue goes away.

author: @hedleypanama
text: #HoldIt!  Just a clarification \t does not mean "in Python" "tab", it is just a regular expression: The backslash modifier is called "escape" and it converts special characters (parenthesis, brackets, ?, ., $, ^ and the backslash itself), so called "metacharacters" into literals and viceversa.  Other literals with special meaning given by the escape or backslash metacharacter: \d Number \D not a number \w any printable character \W any non-printable character \s any non printable character \n new paragraph \1 in some languages it means "first capture" in other languages it can be represented by $1 \3 in some languages it means "third capture" in other languages it can be represented by $3
